04760nam a22007695i 9781501726675DE-B159720190430100931.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190430s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017266757 a10.7591/97815017266752doi  a(DE-B1597)515288  a(OCoLC)1100442669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ766.3b.T44 2004eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh 7aREL0100002bisacsh 7aSOC0460002bisacsh04a241/.662231 aTentler, Leslie Woodcock, eauthor.10aCatholics and Contraception :bAn American History /cLeslie Woodcock Tentler. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2009  a1 online resource :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCushwa Center Studies of Catholicism in Twentieth-Century America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Cornell Paperbacks Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tGlossary -- tIntroduction -- t1. "The Abominable Crime of Onan": Catholic Pastoral Practice and Family Limitation, 1873-1919 -- t2. A Certain Indocility: Obstacles to Reform, 1919-1930 -- t3. "No Longer a Time for Reticence": A Pivotal Decade, 1930-1941 -- t4. "Life Is a Warfare": Confession, Preaching, Politics, 1941-1962 -- t5. "It Isn't Easy to Be a Catholic": Rhythm, Education for Marriage, Lay Voices, 1941-1962 -- t6. The Church's First Duty Is Charity: The "People of God" in a Time of Upheaval, 1962-July 1968 -- tEpilogue: Humanae Vitae and Its Aftermath -- tNotes -- tIndex  aAs Americans rethought sex in the twentieth century, the Catholic Church's teachings on the divisive issue of contraception in marriage were in many ways central. In a fascinating history, Leslie Woodcock Tentler traces changing attitudes: from the late nineteenth century, when religious leaders of every variety were largely united in their opposition to contraception; to the 1920s, when distillations of Freud and the works of family planning reformers like Margaret Sanger began to reach a popular audience; to the Depression years, during which even conservative Protestant denominations quietly dropped prohibitions against marital birth control.Catholics and Contraception carefully examines the intimate dilemmas of pastoral counseling in matters of sexual conduct. Tentler makes it clear that uneasy negotiations were always necessary between clerical and lay authority. As the Catholic Church found itself isolated in its strictures against contraception-and the object of damaging rhetoric in the public debate over legal birth control-support of the Church's teachings on contraception became a mark of Catholic identity, for better and for worse.Tentler draws on evidence from pastoral literature, sermons, lay writings, private correspondence, and interviews with fifty-six priests ordained between 1938 and 1968, concluding, "the recent history of American Catholicism... can only be understood by taking birth control into account." The paperback edition includes a new preface by the author.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Apr 2019) 0aBirth controlxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aBirth controlzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aContraceptionxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aContraceptionzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501726675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501726675.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  